  "node-1768851372669-vtaks563d": {
    "id": "node-1768851372669-vtaks563d",
    "type": "article",
    "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indian_subcontinent",
    "title": "Indian subcontinent",
    "content": "The Indian subcontinent is a massive geographical region in South Asia, defined primarily by the Indian Plate. It encompasses the countries of India, Pakistan, Bangladesh, Nepal, Bhutan, Sri Lanka, and the Maldives. Geographically, it is demarcated by the Himalayas in the north and the Indian Ocean surrounding the peninsula. The region is characterized by immense cultural, linguistic, and religious diversity, having been the birthplace of major world religions like Hinduism, Buddhism, Jainism, and Sikhism. Its history is marked by ancient civilizations, powerful empires, and colonial rule, leading to the modern political map of independent nations.",
    "snippet": "The Indian subcontinent, also known as South Asia, is a peninsular region in Southern Asia, generally considered to project southwards from the main body of the Eurasian continent, lying south of the Himalayas. It is bordered by the mountains to the north and the Indian Ocean to the south, east, and west.",
    "created_at": "2026-01-19T19:36:12.671993Z",
